# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# WHAT IS roarr AND WHY IS IT THE 58TH TS-NODE CLI LIBRARY?
#
# Roarr (https://github.com/gajus/roarr, 856+ stars, ~15M weekly
# downloads) is **Gajus Kuizinas's "JSON-line structured logger
# for Node.js and browsers"** — designed explicitly for
# DISTRIBUTED SYSTEMS where logs are piped to external
# aggregators rather than processed within the application.
# Where Winston/Pino/Consola/Bunyan provide transports +
# formatters + pretty-printers in-process, Roarr emits MINIMAL
# JSON LINES to stdout/stderr and DELEGATES all processing to
# downstream pipelines (@roarr/cli, fluentd, vector, elastic-
# search, etc.).
#
# Roarr's distinguishing characteristics:
#
#   1. MINIMAL JSON-LINE FORMAT — Roarr emits a fixed JSON
#      schema per log line, with no formatter customization:
#
#          {
#            "context": { "package": "turbowatch", "namespace": "main" },
#            "message": "file changed: %s",
#            "sequence": 12,
#            "time": 1717545600000,
#            "version": "2.0.0"
#          }
#
#      The schema is locked at v2 — every Roarr log line has
#      EXACTLY these five fields.  Compare:
#         * Winston: custom format chains via winston.format
#                     (combine, timestamp, json, simple, etc.)
#         * Bunyan: nested object format with `hostname` + `pid`
#         * Pino: configurable serializers + redaction
#         * Consola: pretty-print formatter with badge/symbol
#         * Roarr: LOCKED v2 schema — no in-process formatting
#      FIRST documented Node.js logger with LOCKED IMMUTABLE
#      schema (no custom formatters / serializers).
#
#   2. .child() CONTEXT INHERITANCE — Roarr's central API is
#      `.child({ context })`, which creates a child logger
#      that prepends its context to every log line:
#
#          import { Roarr } from 'roarr';
#
#          // turbowatch's actual Logger.ts:
#          const Logger = Roarr.child({ package: 'turbowatch' });
#
#          // Subscribe handler creates a child of Logger:
#          const log = Logger.child({ namespace: 'subscription' });
#
#          log.info('file matched: %s', filename);
#          // Output: {"context":{"package":"turbowatch","namespace":"subscription"},
#          //          "message":"file matched: src/foo.ts","sequence":1,
#          //          "time":1717545600000,"version":"2.0.0"}
#
#      Context is INHERITED + MERGED — child contexts add to
#      parent contexts without overwriting them.  Compare:
#         * Winston: `winston.createLogger({ defaultMeta: { ... } })`
#         * Bunyan: `bunyan.createLogger({}).child({ ... })`
#                   (Bunyan ALSO has .child but no context merging)
#         * Pino: `pino().child({ ... })` (similar but Pino's
#                  child is a separate stream)
#         * Consola: `createConsola({ defaults: { tag: '...' } })`
#         * Roarr: `.child({ context })` — context CHAIN, every
#                   .child() merges with parent contexts up the
#                   chain to the root Roarr instance
#      FIRST documented Node.js logger with CHAIN-MERGED
#      context inheritance as the central API.
#
#   3. ASYNC LOCAL STORAGE INTEGRATION — Roarr's `getLogContext`
#      hook integrates with Node.js `AsyncLocalStorage` for
#      per-async-context log enrichment.  This lets you set
#      a request-ID at the entry of a request handler and have
#      EVERY downstream log line within that async context
#      automatically include the request-ID:
#
#          import { AsyncLocalStorage } from 'node:async_hooks';
#          import { ROARR } from 'roarr';
#
#          const als = new AsyncLocalStorage<{ requestId: string }>();
#
#          ROARR.getLogContext = () => als.getStore() ?? {};
#
#          // In request handler:
#          als.run({ requestId: 'abc-123' }, async () => {
#              log.info('processing request');
#              // Output includes "requestId":"abc-123" in context
#              await processRequest();
#              // ALL nested logs inherit requestId automatically
#          });
#
#      Compare:
#         * Winston: no built-in ALS — requires winston-context
#                     plugin
#         * Bunyan: no ALS integration
#         * Pino: pino-http has request-scoped context but
#                  general ALS requires asyncLocalStorage option
#         * Consola: no ALS integration
#         * Roarr: AsyncLocalStorage integration is a FIRST-CLASS
#                   primitive via ROARR.getLogContext hook
#      FIRST documented Node.js logger with AsyncLocalStorage
#      integration as a built-in primitive (no plugin required).
#
#   4. DESIGN-FOR-DISTRIBUTED-SYSTEMS PHILOSOPHY — Roarr's
#      README explicitly states: "Roarr is designed for use in
#      distributed systems... logs should be processed by a
#      log aggregator." This is a DELIBERATE departure from
#      Winston's "configure transports + formatters in your
#      application" model.  Roarr emits JSON, you pipe it
#      somewhere else:
#
#          # Recommended Roarr workflow:
#          ROARR_LOG=true node app.js | @roarr/cli --filter '...'
#          # OR pipe to fluentd / vector / vector.dev
#          ROARR_LOG=true node app.js | vector --config vec.toml
#          # OR pipe to a log aggregator's HTTP ingest
#          ROARR_LOG=true node app.js | curl -X POST -d @- ...
#
#      The ROARR_LOG environment variable is a kill-switch:
#      when unset, Roarr emits NOTHING (zero overhead) — when
#      set to "true", JSON lines stream to stdout.  Compare:
#         * Winston: in-process transports (File, Console, HTTP,
#                     Syslog, etc.) — Winston processes logs IN
#                     your application
#         * Bunyan: similar to Winston but pioneered the "pipe
#                    to bunyan CLI" pattern (Roarr borrows this)
#         * Pino: in-process plus worker-thread transports
#         * Consola: reporter plugins in-process
#         * Roarr: ZERO in-process processing — emit + delegate
#      FIRST documented Node.js logger with explicit "log first,
#      transport NEVER (delegate everything)" design philosophy.
#
#   5. GAJUS KUIZINAS ECOSYSTEM PROVENANCE — Roarr is by Gajus
#      Kuizinas (gajus on GitHub), author of the Slonik PostgreSQL
#      ecosystem + global-agent (HTTP proxy agent) + fastify-
#      webpack-hot + 100+ Node.js libraries.  Roarr is the
#      canonical logger across Gajus's entire ecosystem:
#         * Slonik (PostgreSQL client) — Roarr for query logging
#         * Slonik SQL tag raw — Roarr for SQL emission
#         * global-agent — Roarr for proxy decisions
#         * Turbowatch (THIS) — Roarr for file-change events
#         * fastify-webpack-hot — Roarr for HMR events
#         * roarr-cli — companion CLI for filtering Roarr JSON
#      Beyond the Gajus ecosystem, Roarr has been adopted by:
#         * invoke-ai/InvokeAI (Stable Diffusion frontend)
#         * Xcraft-Inc/global-agent (proxy variant)
#         * nodeexx/code-snippet-sharing
#         * knot-dots/knot-dots
#         * sebinsua/modern-node-app
#         * 1000+ Node.js services
#      FIRST documented Node.js logger with this specific
#      "Gajus Kuizinas distributed-systems-first" provenance.
#
# Roarr's relationship to other documented TS-Node Axis 9 libraries:
#
#   * Unlike consola (R576) — consola is unified pretty/browser
#                                logger with reporter pluggability;
#                                Roarr is JSON-only with delegated
#                                processing
#   * Unlike winston (R580) — winston is multi-transport in-
#                               process pipeline; Roarr is
#                               emit-and-pipe
#   * Unlike pino (R584) — pino is high-perf JSON with worker
#                            transports; Roarr is JSON with NO
#                            transports
#   * Unlike debug (R592) — debug is namespace-only conditional
#                             with TEXT output; Roarr is JSON +
#                             context-merging child loggers
#   * Closest cross-language analogs:
#         * Go: rs/zerolog — chained `.With().Str(...).Logger()`
#                              context inheritance is closest match
#         * Rust: tracing — span-based context propagation is
#                            closest match
#         * Python: structlog — bind() context propagation closest
#     Roarr is the FIRST documented Node.js logger with explicit
#     chain-merged context inheritance + AsyncLocalStorage
#     integration + delegated-processing distributed-systems
#     philosophy.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# THE turbowatch CLI — yargs wrapper + roarr Logger + jiti TS loader
#
# turbowatch's CLI is in src/bin/turbowatch.ts.  The yargs command
# tree is:
#
#     const argv = await yargs(hideBin(process.argv))
#         .command('$0 [patterns...]', 'Start Turbowatch',
#                  (commandYargs) => {
#             commandYargs.positional('patterns', {
#                 array: true,
#                 default: ['turbowatch.ts'],
#                 describe:
#                   'Script with Turbowatch instructions. ' +
#                   'Can provide multiple. It can also be a ' +
#                   'glob pattern, e.g. **/turbowatch.ts',
#                 type: 'string',
#             });
#         })
#         .parse();
#
# So turbowatch's CLI surface is:
#   turbowatch [patterns...]     # positional patterns (glob OK)
#   turbowatch                    # defaults to ['turbowatch.ts']
#   turbowatch '**/turbowatch.ts' # multi-pattern
#   turbowatch --help             # yargs auto-generated help
#   turbowatch --version          # yargs auto-generated version
#
# The patterns are TypeScript configuration files (loadable
# via jiti) that export a default `TurbowatchConfigurationInput`
# describing subscriptions + onChange handlers.
#
# Logging gating: turbowatch warns on startup if `ROARR_LOG !=
# 'true'`:
#   [turbowatch] running turbowatch without logging enabled;
#   set ROARR_LOG=true to enable logging. Install @roarr/cli
#   to pretty-print logs.
# When ROARR_LOG=true, Roarr emits JSON lines to stdout for
# each subscribed file-change event + spawn lifecycle event.
#
# Five-axis distinctness from every other documented TS-Node
# Axis 9 logger:
#
#   1. LOCKED IMMUTABLE v2 SCHEMA — Every other documented TS-
#      Node logger supports custom formatters/serializers.
#      Roarr's schema is locked to exactly 5 fields (context,
#      message, sequence, time, version).
#
#   2. CHAIN-MERGED .child() CONTEXT INHERITANCE — Every other
#      documented TS-Node logger has no chain-merged context.
#      Roarr's .child() chains contexts up to the root.
#
#   3. AsyncLocalStorage AS FIRST-CLASS PRIMITIVE — Every other
#      documented TS-Node logger requires plugins for ALS.
#      Roarr's ROARR.getLogContext is a built-in primitive.
#
#   4. ZERO IN-PROCESS PROCESSING — Every other documented TS-
#      Node logger does in-process formatting/transport.  Roarr
#      emits JSON and DELEGATES everything else.
#
#   5. GAJUS-DISTRIBUTED-SYSTEMS PROVENANCE — Every other
#      documented TS-Node logger has different provenance.
#      Roarr is by Gajus Kuizinas with explicit distributed-
#      systems-first design.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# COMMAND-LINE OPTIONS (sourced directly from
# https://github.com/gajus/turbowatch/blob/master/src/bin/turbowatch.ts
# yargs command tree.)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
typeset -A opt_args

_arguments -C \
    '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
    '(- *)--version[show version number]' \
    '*: :_files -g "*.{ts,js,mjs,cjs}"' \
    && ret=0

return ret
